## Description {#details}

This pass exposes codegen information to IR-level passes.

Every transformation that uses codegen information is broken into three parts:
<ul>
<li>The IR-level analysis pass.</li>
<li>The IR-level transformation interface which provides the needed information.</li>
<li>Codegen-level implementation which uses target-specific hooks.</li>
</ul>


This file defines #2, which is the interface that IR-level transformations use for querying the codegen.

<Link id="l00270" /><CodeLine lineNumber="270"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// Underlying constants for &#39;cost&#39; values in this interface.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00271" /><CodeLine lineNumber="271"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00272" /><CodeLine lineNumber="272"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// Many APIs in this interface return a cost. This enum defines the</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00273" /><CodeLine lineNumber="273"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// fundamental values that should be used to interpret (and produce) those</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00274" /><CodeLine lineNumber="274"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// costs. The costs are returned as an int rather than a member of this</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00275" /><CodeLine lineNumber="275"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// enumeration because it is expected that the cost of one IR instruction</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00276" /><CodeLine lineNumber="276"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// may have a multiplicative factor to it or otherwise won&#39;t fit directly</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00277" /><CodeLine lineNumber="277"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// into the enum. Moreover, it is common to sum or average costs which works</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00278" /><CodeLine lineNumber="278"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// better as simple integral values. Thus this enum only provides constants.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00279" /><CodeLine lineNumber="279"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// Also note that the returned costs are signed integers to make it natural</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00280" /><CodeLine lineNumber="280"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// to add, subtract, and test with zero (a common boundary condition). It is</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00281" /><CodeLine lineNumber="281"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// not expected that 2^32 is a realistic cost to be modeling at any point.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00282" /><CodeLine lineNumber="282"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00283" /><CodeLine lineNumber="283"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// Note that these costs should usually reflect the intersection of code-size</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00284" /><CodeLine lineNumber="284"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// cost and execution cost. A free instruction is typically one that folds</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00285" /><CodeLine lineNumber="285"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// into another instruction. For example, reg-to-reg moves can often be</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00286" /><CodeLine lineNumber="286"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// skipped by renaming the registers in the CPU, but they still are encoded</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00287" /><CodeLine lineNumber="287"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// and thus wouldn&#39;t be considered &#39;free&#39; here.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00288" /><CodeLine lineNumber="288" lineLink="/docs/api/classes/llvm/targettransforminfo/#ac44f6b9fdbb5f9cc199f8329cb0b272c"><Highlight kind="normal">  </Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">enum</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/targettransforminfo/#ac44f6b9fdbb5f9cc199f8329cb0b272c">TargetCostConstants</a> &#123;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00289" /><CodeLine lineNumber="289" lineLink="/docs/api/classes/llvm/targettransforminfo/#ac44f6b9fdbb5f9cc199f8329cb0b272ca89f768b1267e3083b4eb05b4ab77e717"><Highlight kind="normal">    <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/targettransforminfo/#ac44f6b9fdbb5f9cc199f8329cb0b272ca89f768b1267e3083b4eb05b4ab77e717">TCC&#95;Free</a> = 0,     </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">///&lt; Expected to fold away in lowering.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00290" /><CodeLine lineNumber="290" lineLink="/docs/api/classes/llvm/targettransforminfo/#ac44f6b9fdbb5f9cc199f8329cb0b272cae46c9eecc49bd2dc253c607e78a0fb86"><Highlight kind="normal">    <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/targettransforminfo/#ac44f6b9fdbb5f9cc199f8329cb0b272cae46c9eecc49bd2dc253c607e78a0fb86">TCC&#95;Basic</a> = 1,    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">///&lt; The cost of a typical &#39;add&#39; instruction.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00291" /><CodeLine lineNumber="291" lineLink="/docs/api/classes/llvm/targettransforminfo/#ac44f6b9fdbb5f9cc199f8329cb0b272ca022565d444ccf496c0414bccefbcd9c8"><Highlight kind="normal">    <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/targettransforminfo/#ac44f6b9fdbb5f9cc199f8329cb0b272ca022565d444ccf496c0414bccefbcd9c8">TCC&#95;Expensive</a> = 4 </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">///&lt; The cost of a &#39;div&#39; instruction on x86.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00988" /><CodeLine lineNumber="988"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// the standard register size, but it cannot be loaded with just one load</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00989" /><CodeLine lineNumber="989"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// instruction. For example, if the size of the memory comparison is 6</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00993" /><CodeLine lineNumber="993"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// approach simplifies the process and produces the comparison result as</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l01316" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1316"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// This is an approximation of reciprocal throughput of a math/logic op.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01317" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1317"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// A higher cost indicates less expected throughput.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01318" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1318"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// From Agner Fog&#39;s guides, reciprocal throughput is &quot;the average number of</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01319" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1319"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// clock cycles per instruction when the instructions are not part of a</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01320" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1320"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// limiting dependency chain.&quot;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01321" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1321"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// Therefore, costs should be scaled to account for multiple execution units</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01322" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1322"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// on the target that can process this type of instruction. For example, if</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01323" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1323"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// there are 5 scalar integer units and 2 vector integer units that can</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01324" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1324"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// calculate an &#39;add&#39; in a single cycle, this model should indicate that the</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01325" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1325"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// cost of the vector add instruction is 2.5 times the cost of the scalar</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01326" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1326"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// add instruction.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01327" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1327"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// \\p Args is an optional argument which holds the instruction operands</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01328" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1328"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// values so the TTI can analyze those values searching for special</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01329" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1329"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// cases or optimizations based on those values.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01330" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1330"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// \\p CxtI is the optional original context instruction, if one exists, to</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01331" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1331"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// provide even more information.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01332" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1332"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// \\p TLibInfo is used to search for platform specific vector library</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01333" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1333"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// functions for instructions that might be converted to calls (e.g. frem).</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l01369" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1369"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// Represents a hint about the context in which a cast is used.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01370" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1370"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01371" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1371"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// For zext/sext, the context of the cast is the operand, which must be a</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01372" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1372"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// load of some kind. For trunc, the context is of the cast is the single</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01373" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1373"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// user of the instruction, which must be a store of some kind.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01374" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1374"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01375" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1375"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// This enum allows the vectorizer to give getCastInstrCost an idea of the</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01376" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1376"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// type of cast it&#39;s dealing with, as not every cast is equal. For instance,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01377" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1377"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// the zext of a load may be free, but the zext of an interleaving load can</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01378" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1378"><Highlight kind="comment">  //// be (very) expensive!</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01379" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1379"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01380" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1380"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// See \\c getCastContextHint to compute a CastContextHint from a cast</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01381" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1381"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// Instruction&#42;. Callers can use it if they don&#39;t need to override the</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01382" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1382"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// context and just want it to be calculated from the instruction.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01383" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1383"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01384" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1384"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// FIXME: This handles the types of load/store that the vectorizer can</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01385" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1385"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// produce, which are the cases where the context instruction is most</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01386" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1386"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// likely to be incorrect. There are other situations where that can happen</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01387" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1387"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// too, which might be handled here but in the long run a more general</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01388" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1388"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// solution of costing multiple instructions at the same times may be better.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l01556" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1556"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// Calculate the cost of vector reduction intrinsics.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01557" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1557"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01558" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1558"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// This is the cost of reducing the vector value of type \\p Ty to a scalar</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01559" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1559"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// value using the operation denoted by \\p Opcode. The FastMathFlags</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01560" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1560"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// parameter \\p FMF indicates what type of reduction we are performing:</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01561" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1561"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///   1 Tree-wise. This is the typical &#39;fast&#39; reduction performed that</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01562" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1562"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///   involves successively splitting a vector into half and doing the</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01563" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1563"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///   operation on the pair of halves until you have a scalar value. For</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01564" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1564"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///   example:</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01565" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1565"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///     (v0, v1, v2, v3)</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01566" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1566"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///     ((v0+v2), (v1+v3), undef, undef)</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01567" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1567"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///     ((v0+v2+v1+v3), undef, undef, undef)</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01568" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1568"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///   This is the default behaviour for integer operations, whereas for</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01569" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1569"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///   floating point we only do this if \\p FMF indicates that</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01570" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1570"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///   reassociation is allowed.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01571" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1571"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///   2 Ordered. For a vector with N elements this involves performing N</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01572" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1572"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///   operations in lane order, starting with an initial scalar value, i.e.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01573" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1573"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///     result = InitVal + v0</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01574" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1574"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///     result = result + v1</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01575" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1575"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///     result = result + v2</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01576" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1576"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///     result = result + v3</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01577" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1577"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///   This is only the case for FP operations and when reassociation is not</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01578" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1578"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///   allowed.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01579" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1579"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01580" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1580"><Highlight kind="normal">  <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/instructioncost">InstructionCost</a> <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/targettransforminfo/#a421ee26483edf3fd0cd1dca34513f45e">getArithmeticReductionCost</a>(</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01581" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1581"><Highlight kind="normal">      </Highlight><Highlight kind="keywordtype">unsigned</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> Opcode, <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/vectortype">VectorType</a> &#42;Ty, std::optional&lt;FastMathFlags&gt; FMF,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01582" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1582"><Highlight kind="normal">      <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/targettransforminfo/#a706f223f760b55668fbae74202b816bb">TTI::TargetCostKind</a> <a href="/docs/api/files/lib/lib/analysis/costmodel-cpp/#a162d8b2b3865594d1e14d828d2b8336a">CostKind</a> = <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/targettransforminfo/#a706f223f760b55668fbae74202b816bba59b32ea7b6f10564abd40ad90602ca5b">TTI::TCK&#95;RecipThroughput</a>) </Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">const</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal">;</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l01584" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1584"><Highlight kind="normal">  <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/instructioncost">InstructionCost</a> <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/targettransforminfo/#a6da1f2e3b471cce50680e800c05e4d6b">getMinMaxReductionCost</a>(</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l01586" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1586"><Highlight kind="normal">      <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/targettransforminfo/#a706f223f760b55668fbae74202b816bb">TTI::TargetCostKind</a> <a href="/docs/api/files/lib/lib/analysis/costmodel-cpp/#a162d8b2b3865594d1e14d828d2b8336a">CostKind</a> = <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/targettransforminfo/#a706f223f760b55668fbae74202b816bba59b32ea7b6f10564abd40ad90602ca5b">TTI::TCK&#95;RecipThroughput</a>) </Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">const</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal">;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01587" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1587"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01588" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1588"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// Calculate the cost of an extended reduction pattern, similar to</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l03183" /><CodeLine lineNumber="3183"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Analysis pass providing the \\c TargetTransformInfo.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l03184" /><CodeLine lineNumber="3184"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l03185" /><CodeLine lineNumber="3185"><Highlight kind="comment">/// The core idea of the TargetIRAnalysis is to expose an interface through</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l03186" /><CodeLine lineNumber="3186"><Highlight kind="comment">/// which LLVM targets can analyze and provide information about the middle</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l03187" /><CodeLine lineNumber="3187"><Highlight kind="comment">/// end&#39;s target-independent IR. This supports use cases such as target-aware</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l03188" /><CodeLine lineNumber="3188"><Highlight kind="comment">/// cost modeling of IR constructs.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l03189" /><CodeLine lineNumber="3189"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l03190" /><CodeLine lineNumber="3190"><Highlight kind="comment">/// This is a function analysis because much of the cost modeling for targets</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l03191" /><CodeLine lineNumber="3191"><Highlight kind="comment">/// is done in a subtarget specific way and LLVM supports compiling different</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l03192" /><CodeLine lineNumber="3192"><Highlight kind="comment">/// functions targeting different subtargets in order to support runtime</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l03193" /><CodeLine lineNumber="3193"><Highlight kind="comment">/// dispatch according to the observed subtarget.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l03194" /><CodeLine lineNumber="3194" lineLink="/docs/api/classes/llvm/targetiranalysis"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">class </Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"><a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/targetiranalysis/#abe59727f7716a4af041daffad2b92a74">TargetIRAnalysis</a> : </Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">public</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/analysisinfomixin">AnalysisInfoMixin</a>&lt;TargetIRAnalysis&gt; &#123;</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l03231" /><CodeLine lineNumber="3231"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l03232" /><CodeLine lineNumber="3232"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// We use a completely opaque callback so that targets can provide whatever</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l03233" /><CodeLine lineNumber="3233"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// mechanism they desire for constructing the TTI for a given function.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l03234" /><CodeLine lineNumber="3234"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l03235" /><CodeLine lineNumber="3235"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// FIXME: Should we really use std::function? It&#39;s relatively inefficient.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l03236" /><CodeLine lineNumber="3236"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// It might be possible to arrange for even stateful callbacks to outlive</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l03237" /><CodeLine lineNumber="3237"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// the analysis and thus use a function&#95;ref which would be lighter weight.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l03238" /><CodeLine lineNumber="3238"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// This may also be less error prone as the callback is likely to reference</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l03239" /><CodeLine lineNumber="3239"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// the external TargetMachine, and that reference needs to never dangle.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l03246" /><CodeLine lineNumber="3246"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Wrapper pass for TargetTransformInfo.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l03247" /><CodeLine lineNumber="3247"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
